# Grammar-Constrained Decoding Can Jailbreak LLMs into Generating Malicious Code

Official implementation of our paper "Grammar-Constrained Decoding Can Jailbreak LLMs into Generating Malicious Code".

<p align="center">
    <a href="https://www.python.org/">
        <img alt="Python" src="https://img.shields.io/badge/Python-3.11+-1f425f.svg?color=purple">
    </a>
    <a href="https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT">
        <img alt="License" src="https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-blue">
    </a>
</p>

## 📰 News

* **[Jun, 2026]**: We've released the code for our paper "Grammar-Constrained Decoding Can Jailbreak LLMs into Generating Malicious Code".

## 👋 Overview

**CodeSpear** is a comprehensive evaluation framework for assessing the safety of large language models (LLMs) against malicious code generation requests. By leveraging **grammar-constrained decoding(GCD)** — a technique originally designed for structured output generation — we demonstrate that attackers can systematically jailbreak LLMs into producing harmful code (e.g., malware, ransomware, keyloggers) across multiple programming languages.

Our framework implements **GCD attack strategies**. We evaluate this strategy on two malicious code benchmarks (**MalwareBench** and **RMCBench**), revealing critical safety vulnerabilities in both open-source and commercial LLMs.

![alt text](assets/codespear.png)

And we got some exciting results!

![alt text](assets/codespear_results.png)

To counter these threats, we also introduce **CodeShield**, a defense mechanism that uses safety fine-tuning to defend against malicious code generation attacks.

![alt text](assets/codeshield.png)

Indeed, our defense model matains strong safety against our GCD attack.

![alt text](assets/codeshield_results.png)

The project includes:
- **Attack / LocalModels** — Run our jailbreak method against HuggingFace models with `llguidance`-based constrained decoding
- **Attack / APIModels** — Run and Evaluate commercial APIs (OpenAI GPT-5, Fireworks.AI) with grammar-constrained tool use
- **Defense** — DPO training data construction and safety fine-tuning to defend against attacks

## 📂 Directory Structure

```
CodeSpear-CodeShield/
├── Attack/
│   ├── APIModels/                # Commercial API evaluation (to be released)
│   ├── LocalModels/              # Local HuggingFace model evaluation
│   │   ├── grammars/             # Lark grammar files for constrained decoding
│   │   │   ├── python.lark
│   │   │   ├── python_no_comments.lark
│   │   │   ├── java.lark
│   │   │   ├── c.lark
│   │   │   ├── cpp.lark
│   │   │   └── go.lark
│   │   ├── models/               # Local model checkpoints here
│   │   └── script/               # Run & evaluation scripts
│   │       ├── run_main.py       # Main entry point
│   │       ├── run_parallel.sh   # Multi-GPU parallel launcher with sharding
│   │       ├── run.sh            # Example single-GPU commands
│   │       ├── eval.sh           # Example evaluation commands
│   │       ├── evaluate_asr.py   # ASR evaluation (DeepSeek judge)
│   │       ├── evaluate_mr.py    # MR evaluation (DeepSeek judge)
│   │       └── merge_shards.py   # Merge sharded results
│   ├── prompt/                   # Prompt datasets (xlsx format)
│   │   ├── test/                 # Test prompts (RMCBench, MalwareBench, PKU-SafeRLHF)
│   │   └── train/                # Training prompts
│   └── .env.example              # API key template
├── Defense/
│   └── build_training_data.py    # DPO training data construction
├── pyproject.toml
├── LICENSE
└── README.md
```

## 🚀 Environment Setup

Install dependencies via `uv` (recommended) or `pip`:

```bash
# Using uv (recommended)
uv sync

# Using pip
pip install -e
```

For local model evaluation, you also need `llguidance`:

```bash
pip install llguidance
```

### API Keys

Copy the environment template and set your API keys:

```bash
cp Attack/.env.example Attack/.env
# Edit Attack/.env with your actual API keys
```

Required environment variables:
- `OPENAI_API_KEY` — OpenAI API key
- `FIREWORKS_API_KEY` — Fireworks.AI API key
- `DEEPSEEK_API_KEY` — DeepSeek API key (for evaluation judges)

## 💽 Usage

### Attack: Local Model Evaluation

All commands are run from the `Attack/LocalModels/` directory.

```bash
cd Attack/LocalModels

# Run strategy 1 (grammar-constrained) on RMC benchmark (Python) with model index 5
CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES=0 python script/run_main.py \
    --run_model_index 5 --strategy 1 --codelang py --benchmark rmc

# Run multiple strategies on all benchmarks
CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES=0 python script/run_main.py \
    --run_model_index 0 --strategy 0 1 --codelang py --benchmark total

# Multi-GPU parallel run with 8 GPUs and automatic sharding
RUN_MODEL_INDEX=5 STRATEGY="0 1" BENCHMARK=total bash script/run_parallel.sh
```

**Key arguments for `run_main.py`:**

| Argument | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `--run_model_index` | Model index (see model index table below) |
| `--strategy` | Attack strategy ID(s): 0–10 (see strategy table) |
| `--benchmark` | Benchmark: `rmc`, `mal`, `pku`, `total` (= rmc + mal), `trainset` |
| `--codelang` | Programming language: `py`, `cpp`, `java` (default: `py`) |
| `--run_rounds` | Number of experiment rounds (default: 1) |
| `--num_shards` / `--shard_id` | Data-parallel sharding for multi-GPU runs |
| `--quiet_generation` | Suppress per-token generation output |

**Model index mapping:**

| Index | Model |
|-------|-------|
| 0 | Meta-Llama-3-8B-Instruct |
| 1 | Meta-Llama-3-70B-Instruct |
| 2 | Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct |
| 3 | Qwen2.5-14B-Instruct |
| 4 | Qwen2.5-32B-Instruct |
| 5 | Qwen2.5-Coder-7B-Instruct |
| 6 | Qwen2.5-Coder-14B-Instruct |
| 7 | Qwen2.5-Coder-32B-Instruct |
| 8 | Qwen2.5-Coder-7B-Instruct-defended |
| 9 | Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct-defended |
| 10 | Meta-Llama-3-8B-Instruct-defended |
| 11 | Qwen2.5-Coder-7B-Instruct-baseline1 |
| 12 | Qwen2.5-Coder-7B-Instruct-baseline2 |

### Attack: Evaluate Results

```bash
cd Attack/LocalModels

# Evaluate Malicious Ratio (MR)
python script/evaluate_mr.py \
    --file_prefix 0 1 --run_model_indexs 0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 --results_group total

# Evaluate Attack Success Rate (ASR)
python script/evaluate_asr.py \
    --file_prefix 0 1 --run_model_indexs 0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 --results_group total
```

### Attack: Merge Sharded Results

```bash
cd Attack/LocalModels

# Merge shards for a specific strategy × benchmark × model
python script/merge_shards.py \
    --strategy 1 --benchmark rmc --model_dir Qwen2.5-Coder-7B-Instruct --cleanup

# Merge with explicit timestamp and prune duplicate run_info
python script/merge_shards.py \
    --strategy 1 --benchmark rmc \
    --model_dir Qwen2.5-Coder-7B-Instruct-defended-method1 \
    --timestamp 20260509093627 --cleanup --prune-run-info
```

### Attack: API Model Evaluation

> ⚠️ The `Attack/APIModels/` module will be released in a future update. Stay tuned.

### Defense: DPO Training Data Construction

```bash
python Defense/build_training_data.py \
    --eval_result  <path/to/eval_result.xlsx> \
    --rejections   <path/to/rejections.xlsx> \
    --sft_source   OCI \
    --sft_data     <path/to/sft_data.json> \
    --malicious_kw <path/to/malicious_keywords.txt> \
    --output_dpo   <path/to/output_dpo.json> \
    --output_sft   <path/to/output_sft.json> \
    --k 1600 --j 5 --SFT 2.5 --seed 42
```

The script builds DPO preference pairs from evaluation results:
1. Identifies responses where the model failed to defend (verdict == BAD)
2. Constructs two-stage DPO pairs: (refusal > code) and (code > malicious)
3. Samples SFT data from OpenCodeInstruct for regularization
4. Outputs in LLaMA-Factory ShareGPT format

## 🎯 Attack Strategies

| ID | Strategy | Description |
|----|----------|-------------|
| 0 | Vanilla | Native generation with chat template |
| 1 | Ours | Grammar-constrained decoding with forced import prefix |
| 2 | Low-Resource Language | Translated prompt (Swahili, etc.) |
| 3 | DAN | "Do Anything Now" jailbreak prompt |
| 4 | Affirmative | Forced affirmative response prefix |
| 5 | Ours + Safety Hint | Strategy 1 + chosen-collection safety instruction |
| 6 | Affirmative+Import | Strategy 1 with affirmative opener |
| 7 | JailTemplate | Pre-transformed jailbreak prompt template |
| 8 | PAIR | Real-time adversarial attack |
| 9 | CodeJailbreaker | Precomputed code jailbreaker transform |
| 10 | APT | Attack Prefix Tree (real-time) |

## 📊 Benchmarks

- **RMCBench**: Refuse Malicious Code Benchmark
- **MalwareBench**: Malicious code generation benchmark
- **PKU-SafeRLHF**: Safety alignment evaluation set

## 📦 Dependencies

- Python 3.11+
- PyTorch 2.x
- transformers
- pandas, openpyxl
- openai
- requests
- python-dotenv
- llguidance (for local model constrained decoding)

